AROMATARIUS.body:
A word formerly used
for a grocer. 1 Vent. 142,

87 ARRAS

AB EPISTOLIS.body:
Lat. An officer having
charge of the correspondence (eptstole) of
his superior or sovereign; a secretary. Calvin.; Splegelias.;

AGGRIEVED.body:
Having suffered loss or
injury; damnified;

AGGRIEVED PARTY. Under statutes
granting the right of appeal to the party
aggrieved by an order or judgment, the party aggrieved is one whose pecuniary interest is directly affected by the adjudication;
one whose right of property may be established or divested thereby. Ruff v. Montgomery, 83 Miss. 185, 36 South. 67; McFarland v. Pierce, 151 Ind. 546, 45 N. E. 706;
Lamar v. Lamar, 118 Ga. 684, 45 S. E. 498;
Smith v. Bradstreet, 16 Pick. (Mass.) 264;
Bryant v. Allen, 6 N. H. 116; Wiggin v.
Swett, 6 Metc. (Mass.) 194, 89 Am. Dec. 716;
Tillinghast v. Brown University, 24 R. I. 179,
52 Atl. 891; Lowery v. Lowery, 64 N. C.
110; Raleigh v. Rogers, 25 N. J. Eq. 506. Or
one against whom error has been committed.
Kinealy v. Macklin, 67 Mo. 95.

ALMESFEOH.body:
In Saxon law. Alms-fee;
alms-money. Otherwise called "Peterpence."
Cowell,

EXLEGARE.body:
In old English law. To
outlaw; to deprive one of the benefit and
protection of the law, (exuere aliquem beneftcio legis.) Spelman.;

FIEL.body:
In Spanish law. A sequestrator;
a person in whose hands a thing in dispute
is judicially deposited; a receiver. Las Partidas, pt. 3, tit. 9, ll. 2.

FORMAL.body:
Relating to matters of form;
as, "formal defects;" inserted, added, or
joined pro forma. See PARITIES.

KAST.body:
In Swedish law. Jettison: a literal translation of the Latin "jactus."
—Kast-geld. Contribution for a jettison;
average.

MARUS.body:
In old Scotch law. A maire;
an officer or executor of summons. Otherwise called "preco regis." Skene.
 MASAGIUM,. L. Lat. A messuage.

OBSCENE.body:
Lewd; fmpure; indecent;
calculated to shock the moral sense of man
by a disregard of chastity or modesty. Timmons v. U. S., 85 Fed. 205, 30.C. GC. A. 74;
U. S. v. Harmon (D. C.) 45 Fed. 414; Dunlop
v. U. S., 165 U. S. 486, 17 Sup. Ct. 875, 41
re Ed. 799; Com. vy. Landis, 8 Phila. (Pa.)

RUPTCY.body:
—Adjudication in implement. An
action by a grantee against his grantor to compel him to complete the title.

